puts in 18-hour days grooming and conditioning his charges and like a racehorse jockey he crisscrosses the country showing the dogs for a variety of owners extra 3 grooming dogs for success couple comb out champ canines also ran in wt12 mcfadden and his wife taffe run their dog handling business in campbell and do it primarily for the enjoyment and satisfaction it brings those who think you can get rich handling dogs are barking up the wrong tree we make a good living but the overhead is high and the hours long before a show we sometimes work around the clock brushing and cleaning the dogs working on their coats said mcfadden and breeds such as poodles have to be highly trimmed mcfadden said he handles an average of 20 to 25 dogs at each show and works around 120 shows a year all over the us the dogs are frequent winners in best of breed and best of show categories we finish with close to 100 champions a year he said as a handler mcfadden emphasizes that he doesn't do obedience training his job is to trim and condition the dogs and prepare them physically and mentally the aim he said is to have a confident and happy dog entering a competition over the last seven years mcfadden and his wife have shown dogs representing approximately 75 percent of the 135 breeds of dog taffe mcfadden a vancouver british columbia native who has been involved in dog handling since she was a child specializes in poodles the couple also owns two standard poodles and breed wire fox terriers mcfadden's latest product a kerry blue terrier named kerrageen's hotspur won the best of show prize at the 81st golden gate kennel club dog show held feb 2-3 at the cow palace in san francisco more than 2000 purebred dogs participated in the national competition it was the 37th best in show win by kerrageen's hotspur making him the top kerry blue terrier of all time the dog is owned by bryan percy and judy hertwell of seattle kerrageen's hotspur was scheduled to join mcfadden in new york city last week 